Name: Richard Irving Berman
PostWarExperience:
Following his discharge from the Navy, Richard  returned to study at Pace University where he earned his Bachelor's of Business Administration, graduating in June of 1950. 

Richard then joined the work force working for the next eight years with two accounting (CPA) firms in the New York City area.

He married his wife Shirley in 1952, and raised three children. 

In 1959 Richard formed a partnership and practiced Public Accounting and Taxation until 1964.  He then opened a solo practice where he practiced until his retirement in 1990.

Richard eventually moved from Long Island to his current location in Mid Hudson, New York in 2003.

His favorite USS Champlin memory is the action surrounding the Wake Island Attack.

Name: Gerald Milton Cruthers
PostWarExperience:
Following his discharge from the Navy, Gerry returned to Connecticut to resume his academic studies at the University of Connecticut, where he graduated in 1950.  Gerry continued his studies at the university and was awarded a Masters degree in the fall of 1950.

Following his marriage to Marilyn Crowell, Gerry accepted a teaching position at his alma mater, Norwich Free Academy, where he taught mathematics. Gerry continued to teach until he retired having completed 28 years of positive influence on his thousands of students.

Never being one to sit back and relax, Gerry soon un-retired and joined A. Robert Schnip and Associates and sold real estate. During this period of time Gerry also found time to study Library Science at Mohegan Community College and became a Professional Genealogist.

Gerry took an active role as a member of The Park Congregational Church in Norwich, serving as Director of Religious Education, as a member of it's executive board, as well as serving on it's Board of Directors.

Gerry passed on July 2, 2005 having fought a long courageous battle with cancer, but, not before having touched and influenced the lives of so many who all remember and speak of him fondly.

Name: Glenn Wesley Detro
Grandchildren: US ARMY Major Mark W. Anders
PostWarExperience:
Before Joining the Navy, Glenn Detro was constructing "Interlake" Sailboats that would sail on Lake Erie.

Glenn was a construction worker who helped build the Sandusky Sailing Clubhouse. His excellent marine accomplishments are still remembered to this day.
World War II stopped all construction of the "Interlakes" though the boats that had been built provided welcome relief for their owners throughout those years.


As joining a military unit became evident, Glenn was heard telling his family:
"If I am to serve I prefer sailing on a ship to walking in the Army."
Thus his hitch in the Navy began.


Following his honorable discharge from the Navy he returned to Sandusky, Ohio. Glenn had built his own home before the War and rented it out while he was living in Massachusetts and Florida. Returning to Sandusky with his wife, Mildred, and daughter, Carol, he resumed his carpentry work. Daughter, Nancy, was born in 1946. He was a self employed contractor, carpenter and millwright. Cedar Point Amusement Park also benefited from his carpentry skills. Some of the most pride and enjoyment came as he worked restoring various boats in the area. He was an active member of the Carpenter's Local No. 940 and the Moose Lodge. 

There was always pride in his voice when he talked about his daughters.  He always wanted the best for them and he implanted a desire in them to succeed in all endeavors.

Glenn's life was cut short when he suffered heart problems and passed away at the early age of 50 on June 28, 1962 in Sandusky, Ohio.

Name: Louis Gilbert (nee Goldberg)
PostWarExperience:
Following the war, Louis returned home, where he married his wife Gloria Haigis.  Lou and Gloria raised four children, and are now Grandparents to seven and Great Grandparents to two more.

Lou spent his working career working in the tool and die making industry.  He worked as  foreman for  Novelty Jewelry and Metal Products as a tool and die machinist .  He later later spent 37 years with Republic Aviation as a machinist and set-up man.  

Over the years Lou worked various part time jobs as well, including: Driving School bus, Dump Truck Driver, working an Ice Cream Truck, and running a Children's Whip Ride. 

Lou's Memories of the USS Champlin and World War II are many, including:

Seeing the World, and spending Liberties in so many Foreign Ports.

Floating in the Middle of the Atlantic Ocean without steam, as the Champlin crew hurried about trying to restore power.

Escorting President Roosevelt to Russia.

Name: Kenneth Roger Kooken
Children: Thomas A Kogan (Kooken) Janet Kooken Fazenbaker
PostWarExperience:
Post World War II Life Experience:

Following his discharge from the service Kenneth returned to employment at the West Virginia Pulp and Paper Mill in Luke Maryland.  He spent 44 years working with the company and finally retired in 1977.  During this period of time Kenneth completed his education and earned his GED.

Socially, Kenneth enjoyed entertaining elderly residents of area nursing homes, and remained very active in his local church.

Name: Robert John Maitre
PostWarExperience:
Following the war Robert returned home, attended Pace College, and eventually married his wife, Patricia Powers in 1954.  They raised three children, and are now grandparents to seven grandchildren.

Robert went to work in the Yonkers Police Department, serving for forty years.  He retired as a Lieutenant in 1989.

Name: Byron Don Probert
PostWarExperience:
After the war he returned home to work on the family ranch with his two brothers, Dick and Carl.

He had a great love for the three-generation ranch and farm operation that he was part owner of, and was kind and caring in his stewardship over his cattle and horses.

Bud and Shirley served a Utah Cove Fort mission at Cove Fort, for The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints from June 1994, to November 1996.

Bud will be remembered for his love and devotion to his wife of 60 years and his family. He was a wonderful husband, father, grandfather, great-grandfather, brother and friend. He is loved very much and will be missed greatly

Name: Owen Denzil Rogers
PostWarExperience:
At the end of the war Denzil returned to Harrodsburg, KY and went to work as a butcher in the family business, Rogers Sausage Company.  The business was founded and ran by his father.  Denzil and his first wife Mary Bell had two children prior to the end of the war, Bill and Nancy.  They added two more children before 1950, Danny and Doug.

Denzil used his GI Bill to purchase a house in Harrodsburg and continued to work in the family business until the late 1950s.  He then worked as a carpenter. 

Following a divorce from his wife, Denzil married Sue and moved to Indiana where he worked as a maintenance man for a motel.  During this time, (1980,s) he became very involved with the Jehovah Witness Church and dedicated a lot of his time to church work in the later years of his life.

Denzil was an avid fisherman and hunter throughout his life.  He was also a very active reader.

He retired to Florida in the late 90"and died there in 2003 of lung cancer.
